  "prompt": "What are the different types of absorbable surgical sutures?",
  "response": "Absorbable surgical sutures are designed to be broken down and assimilated by the body over time, eliminating the need for suture removal. These sutures are commonly used for internal tissue repair where long-term suture strength is not required. There are several types of absorbable sutures, each with its own unique properties and uses. Some of the most common types include:\n\n1. **Polyglactin 910 (Vicryl):**\n   - Made from a copolymer of glycolic acid and lactic acid.\n   - Available in braided or monofilament form.\n   - Absorption typically occurs within 60-90 days.\n   - Commonly used for general soft tissue approximation including ligation and ophthalmic procedures.\n\n2. **Polyglycolic Acid (Dexon):**\n   - Made from a homopolymer of glycolic acid.\n   - Typically available as braided multifilament.\n   - Absorption generally occurs within 60-90 days.\n   - Used for general soft tissue approximation and ligation.\n\n3. **Polydioxanone (PDS II):**\n   - Made from the polymer polydioxanone.\n   - Available as monofilament.\n   - Known for its longer absorption period, usually between 180-210 days.\n   - Used for soft tissue approximation, especially where extended support is desirable.\n\n4. **Polyglyconate (Maxon):**\n   - Made from a copolymer of glycolic acid and trimethylene carbonate.\n   - Monofilament sutures.\n   - Absorption generally occurs within 180-210 days.\n   - Suitable for soft tissue approximation and pediatric cardiovascular surgery.\n\n5. **Polysorb:**\n   - Made from a copolymer of glycolide/lactide.\n   - A braided suture.\n   - Absorption occurs over 56-70 days.\n   - Often used for ligation and general soft tissue approximation.\n\n6. **Catgut:**\n   - Made from purified connective tissue (collagen) of cows or sheep.\n   - Can be plain or chromic-treated (treatment with chromium salts reduces reactivity and extends absorption time).\n   - Plain catgut generally absorbs within 7-10 days, while chromic catgut absorbs within 90-120 days.\n   - Used primarily in internal structures where rapid absorption is required.\n\n7. **Poliglecaprone (Monocryl):**\n   - Made from a copolymer of glycolide and \u03b5-caprolactone.\n   - Monofilament form.\n   - Rapid absorption occurs within 91-119 days.\n   - Ideal for use in subcuticular closure, pediatric cardiovascular surgery, and bowel anastomosis.\n\nThese absorbable sutures differ in terms of composition, duration before they are absorbed, and their applications. The choice of suture material depends on the specific requirements of the surgical procedure and the healing characteristics of the tissue being sutured.",
